    <title>Combined summary - Blinded 2-party Musig2</title>
    <updated>2023-08-02T18:35:14.727162+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2023-July/021821.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The conversation revolves around the security and vulnerabilities of blind signing services, specifically in the context of protocols like MuSig, MuSig2, and FROST. Participants analyze the proposed solutions, raise concerns about potential attacks, and provide suggestions for improving the protocols' security. The need for additional guarantees and proofs to ensure the security and integrity of the blind signing process is emphasized.One proposal involves the client sending a commitment to the public key X2 and proving in zero knowledge that c = SHA256(X1 + X2, R1 + R2, m). However, further exploration is needed to fully evaluate this approach. The concept of "proof of secret key" (posk) is also discussed, with speculation that it could potentially serve as a building block for the secure blind signing scheme.In the case of blinding for party 1, modifications are made to prevent party 1 from learning the full public key or final signature. Key aggregation is performed only by party 2, who receives X1 from party 1. Nonce aggregation is also done by party 2, who receives R1 from party 1. Concerns are raised about this scheme's vulnerability to certain attacks, as MuSig2 requires multiple 'R' points per signatory to prevent those attacks.Another topic of discussion is the implementation of a blinded statechain protocol using Schnorr MuSig2. Potential vulnerabilities in the proposed scheme are highlighted, including an attack where a malicious client manipulates R-values obtained from the server. Tom Trevethan proposes adjustments to the protocol to blind party 1, but there are concerns about the vulnerability of this modified scheme to specific attacks.Overall, the participants highlight the ongoing research and exploration needed to develop robust and secure blind signing services in cryptographic protocols. Further comments and feedback on the proposed adjustments and potential issues are sought.</summary>
